<author><name><![CDATA[qeed]]></name></author>
<updated>2009-09-14T07:52:14-07:00</updated>
<published>2009-09-14T07:52:14-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5566&amp;p=50621#p50621</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5566&amp;p=50621#p50621"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[What methods are there to solve this 'open bus' problem?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=5566&amp;p=50621#p50621"><![CDATA[
I don't think that is open bus. Open bus is when you try to read an address that is not implemented for reading, like some of the PPU regs, or the APU regs, or any address beyond those that are not mapped by the game cartridge itself, like 0x5000 and above up to 0x7FFF. The address $C600 should be mapped however, since that is the prg rom. Since nestest has 1 bank 0xC000 to 0xFFFF is mirrored with 0x8000 to 0xBFFF. The indirect x reads in a pointer way, where it gets the value next from the opcode,in this case 0xFF. then adds x to it (wrapping around, since whatever happens in zero page stays in zero page), then it reads the low and high address to get the real address to read from. Since the pointer can change, the cmp could have an effect, where maybe it is used for some timing purposes to keep bne in a loop. For real open bus addresses, I just returned whatever is read last on the bus, like address lda $5000 would be 0x50, since the last value read is 0x50. Though the PPU open bus is handled a little differently, search for dvdmth posts about open bus and the PPU, where he explains it really thoroughly.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3551">qeed</a> — Mon Sep 14, 2009 7:52 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
